      "updated": 1780987373669,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "const name = \"Sachine\"\n\nconsole.log(\"Hello\" + name);\n\n-> without concatenation of string you can use its value in any line if you want to use.\n\nconst name = \"Geeta\";\n\nconsole.log(`my school name is ${name}`);\n\n-> it is introduced in ES6\n\n-> no need to use \\n for multiple line.\n\nconst line = `my name\nis\nSurya.`\n\nconsole.log(line);\n\n-> you can perform operation on variables within template literal.\n\nlet a = 8, b = 13;\n\nconsole.log(`sum of a and b is ${a + b}`);",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "const name = \"Sachine\"\n\nconsole.log(\"Hello\" + name);\n\n-> without concatenation of string you can use its value in any line if you want to use.\n\nconst name = \"Geeta\";\n\nconsole.log(`my school name is ${name}`);\n\n-> it is introduced in ES6\n\n-> no need to use \\n for multiple line.\n\nconst line = `my name\nis\nSurya.`\n\nconsole.log(line);\n\n-> you can perform operation on variables within template literal.\n\nlet a = 8, b = 13;\n\nconsole.log(`sum of a and b is ${a + b}`);",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
